        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  Define the DocumentMetadata schema — a Pydantic model holding file-level metadata (name, size, timestamps, MIME type, UID) with support for extra attributes. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Document file metadata model. \par \b Input\/ \:  None (standalone model with extra attributes support). \par \b Output\/ \:  Pydantic BaseModel <computeroutput>DocumentMetadata</computeroutput> with uid, file_name, size, timestamps, file_type, plus arbitrary extra fields. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(7): pydantic.BaseModel, pydantic.Extra] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>uid is always a non-empty unique string.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>file_name is always present (original document name).</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Extra fields are preserved and serialized. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why Extra.allow? A: Different document formats carry different metadata (author, pages, etc.). Extra.allow prevents data loss while keeping the schema flexible. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 – Initial creation with semantic markup] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 9[Document metadata with extra attributes support] =&gt; DocumentMetadata \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[DocumentMetadata]: MetadataExtractor =&gt; PopulateMetadata =&gt; ReturnToAPI </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
